The paper deals with the computational complexity of graph planarization, which is a problem in graph theory and computational geometry. The use of MSOL formulas suggests a connection to logic and formal methods, which is reflected in the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) category. The problem of graph planarization is also related to graph algorithms and data structures, which are covered by the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) category. The use of edge contraction as a technique for planarization suggests a connection to graph contraction and graph minors, which are covered by the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) category. The study of the complexity of the problem suggests a connection to computational complexity theory, which is covered by the cs.CC (Computational Complexity) category. Finally, the study of planarization and subgraph contractibility suggests a connection to graph theory and combinatorics, which are covered by the cs.LG (Graph Theory and Combinatorics) category.
